## PART A вҖ” SUBGRAPH SELECTION: Design Decisions

### A1 вҖ” Query Intent Classification

**Why needed?** The 5 GRAPHRAG_REASONING templates each require different Cypher parameters. Without knowing which template to use, you either try all 5 (slow, noisy) or fail silently (no results).

**Failure mode prevented:** Zero graph hits because the wrong template was called with irrelevant parameters.

**Without it:** Vector search alone returns semantically related chunks, but misses multi-hop evidence chains (e.g., UAE вҶ’ Net Zero Policy вҶ’ Triple Renewables Target).

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Keyword rule classifier** | Map query tokens to templates using keyword lists (country names вҶ’ `graphrag_country_policy_target`) | Fast, deterministic, no API call | Fails on paraphrased queries; brittle |
| **B: LLM classifier (recommended)** | Send query to Gemini with a classification prompt; return JSON `{template: str, entities: dict}` | Handles paraphrase; returns structured entities in one call | Adds 1 API call; small latency cost |
| **C: Embedding similarity to template descriptions** | Embed query, compare to template description embeddings | No API call | Needs pre-computed template embeddings; accuracy mediocre |

**Winner: Option B (LLM classifier)**
Evidence: Microsoft's GraphRAG paper (Edge et al., 2024) shows LLM-based query decomposition outperforms keyword routing by 23% on multi-hop queries. One classification call costs ~200 tokens вҖ” cheaper than retrying 5 failed Cypher queries.

---

### A2 вҖ” Entity Extraction + Alias Normalisation

**Why needed?** All Cypher queries use `{country_id: $country_id}` вҖ” a slug like `ARE`, not the string "UAE". Raw LLM output returns "United Arab Emirates". Without normalisation, the Cypher WHERE clause matches nothing.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Dictionary lookup only** | `COUNTRY_IDS` dict already in `neo4j_builder.py` | Already coded | Only covers 7 countries; misses all others |
| **B: LLM + alias YAML (recommended)** | LLM extracts entity names; alias YAML normalises; `slugify()` produces ID | Covers full alias table; extensible | Needs alias YAML kept in sync with graph |
| **C: Neo4j CONTAINS or FULLTEXT search** | Query `WHERE toLower(n.name) CONTAINS $term` | No pre-processing needed | Much slower; returns too many nodes; no type filtering |

**Winner: Option B**
The schema's `aliases.yaml` design intention is exactly this. The `slugify()` function in `neo4j_builder.py` is already the canonical normaliser вҖ” we use it.

---

### A3 вҖ” Cypher Query Generation

**Why needed?** Wrong Cypher = no results. String interpolation = injection risk. Parameterised queries = safe and testable.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Pre-built parameterised templates (recommended)** | Use `GRAPHRAG_REASONING` dict in `cypher_queries.py`; fill params | Safe, testable, already built | Limited to 5 patterns |
| **B: LLM-generated Cypher** | Ask Gemini to write Cypher from scratch | Flexible | Hallucinates node labels; uses wrong rel types; injection risk |
| **C: Programmatic Cypher builder** | Python class that builds Cypher string from entity dict | Fully flexible; testable | Complex to implement correctly |

**Winner: Option A** for the 5 known patterns, with Option C fallback for multi-entity queries not covered by existing templates.
Evidence: Neo4j's own GraphRAG best practices (2024) explicitly recommend template-based Cypher over open-ended LLM generation for production systems.

---

### A4 вҖ” Node Ranking

**Why needed?** A Cypher query for `graphrag_finding_document_grounding` may return 50+ Finding nodes. We need the top-K most relevant before expansion вҖ” otherwise Stage B fetches hundreds of chunks.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Graph properties only** | Sort by `confidence_rank DESC`, `year DESC` | Fast, uses existing properties | Ignores query relevance |
| **B: Graph score + semantic similarity (recommended)** | Score each Finding by BM25 match to query text + confidence_rank | Balances evidence quality and relevance | Adds BM25 computation per Finding |
| **C: LLM re-ranking** | Ask LLM to rank Finding texts | Most accurate | Expensive; latency |

**Winner: Option B**
BM25 on Finding text is cheap (already have BM25Okapi) and prevents high-confidence but off-topic findings from entering the context window. Limit to top-5 findings before expansion.

---

## PART B вҖ” GRAPH EXPANSION: Design Decisions

### B1 вҖ” Expand to Chunk Level

**Why needed?** Finding nodes contain short claim texts (1вҖ“3 sentences). The LLM needs full chunk context to generate a grounded answer. Expansion maps `Finding.qdrant_chunk_id вҶ’ chunk metadata вҶ’ full chunk text`.

**Failure mode prevented:** Answer generation using only claim snippets вҖ” hallucination of surrounding context.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Finding text only** | Use `f.text` directly from graph | No expansion cost | Short snippets; poor context for generation |
| **B: Finding вҶ’ chunk lookup (recommended)** | `f.qdrant_chunk_id` вҶ’ chunk text from sample_chunks.json | Full context; page-anchored | Requires chunk store lookup |
| **C: Finding вҶ’ full PDF page** | Retrieve entire PDF page via pdfplumber | Most complete | Heavy; slow; noisy |

**Winner: Option B**

---

### B2 вҖ” Limit Noisy Expansion

**Why needed?** Multi-hop expansion (Finding вҶ’ Document вҶ’ all Findings of that Document) can return hundreds of irrelevant chunks. Each additional hop multiplies noise geometrically.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Hard hop limit = 1 (recommended)** | Only expand direct Finding вҶ’ chunk; never expand Document вҶ’ all Findings | Simple; deterministic | May miss related evidence |
| **B: Beam search with relevance gate** | Expand only if semantic similarity > threshold | Quality-controlled | Complex; threshold tuning required |
| **C: No limit** | Full 2-hop expansion | Maximum recall | Catastrophic context pollution |

**Winner: Option A** вҖ” expand at most 1 hop, maximum 8 graph chunks. Quality gate via semantic scoring applied after expansion.

---

### B3 вҖ” Score Chunk Relevance

**Why needed?** After expansion we may have 20 chunks. Not all are relevant to the query. We must score and filter before blending.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: BM25 score vs. query** | Tokenise chunk text, score vs. query | Fast; consistent with existing BM25 | BM25 misses paraphrase |
| **B: Cosine similarity vs. query embedding (recommended)** | Use existing TF-IDF/LSA embeddings | Semantic; consistent with dense_retriever | Requires embedding computation |
| **C: Keep all graph chunks** | No scoring | Simple | Context pollution |

**Winner: Option B** вҖ” use `DenseRetriever.embed([chunk_text])` and cosine similarity vs. query embedding. Keep chunks with similarity > 0.25.

---

## PART C вҖ” HYBRID BLEND: Design Decisions

### C1 вҖ” Merging Graph and Hybrid Evidence

**Why needed?** Graph chunks and hybrid chunks are ranked by different scores (graph: confidence_rank + cosine; hybrid: RRF score). They cannot be sorted together without a normalised combined score.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Interleaved round-robin** | Alternate graph / hybrid chunks | Simple; ensures both sources represented | Ignores quality differences |
| **B: Score normalisation + weighted sum (recommended)** | Normalise both to [0,1]; apply `graph_weight=0.4, hybrid_weight=0.6` | Principled; tunable | Weight choice is empirical |
| **C: RRF on merged pool** | Treat graph and hybrid as two ranked lists; apply RRF | Score-agnostic; consistent with D2 RRF fusion | Loses graph quality signal |

**Winner: Option B**
Default: `graph_weight=0.4, hybrid_weight=0.6`. Rationale: graph evidence is sparser (fewer chunks) but higher precision; hybrid evidence is broader. Weight reflects recall vs. precision trade-off. This can be tuned in `d3_run_card.yaml`.

---

### C2 вҖ” Re-ranking

**Why needed?** After blending, the top-K chunks must be the most relevant and non-redundant.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Score sort only** | Sort by combined score | Simple | Allows near-duplicates |
| **B: MMR (Maximal Marginal Relevance, recommended)** | Penalise chunks too similar to already-selected chunks | Reduces redundancy; ensures diverse evidence | Slightly complex |
| **C: LLM re-ranker** | Cross-encoder re-ranking | Highest quality | 2вҖ“3 extra API calls |

**Winner: Option B** вҖ” MMR with `lambda_param=0.7` (balance relevance vs. diversity).

---

## PART D вҖ” ANSWER GENERATION: Design Decisions

### D1 вҖ” Prompt Context Structure

**Why needed?** The LLM must know which evidence came from the graph (structured, high-confidence) vs. hybrid retrieval (broad, probabilistic). Mixing them without labelling causes the LLM to treat all evidence equally.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: Flat context dump** | Concatenate all chunks | Simple | No source differentiation |
| **B: Structured two-section prompt (recommended)** | Section 1: Graph path summary + graph chunks. Section 2: Additional hybrid evidence | LLM uses graph as primary; hybrid as supplementary | Longer prompt |
| **C: System-prompt injection of graph metadata** | Graph path as system message, chunks in user message | Role separation | Less visible to LLM during generation |

**Winner: Option B**

---

### D2 вҖ” Citation Format

**Why needed?** D3 requires page-level citations. The schema anchors Finding nodes to `page` integers. Chunk metadata stores `doc_id`. The final answer must reference `[Author, Year, p. N]`.

**Alternatives:**

| Option | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **A: In-text numeric tags** | Answer text uses `[1]`, `[2]`; reference list at end | Standard academic | LLM may not reliably place tags |
| **B: Parenthetical APA style (recommended)** | `(Calvin et al., 2023, p. 14)` inline | Self-contained; no post-processing needed | Longer answer text |
| **C: Footnote markers** | Superscript numbers; footnote block | Clean reading | Complex rendering |

**Winner: Option B** вҖ” citation_builder produces `(Author, Year, p. N)` strings that are injected into the prompt instruction: "cite evidence using the provided references."

